results.notes: This mushroom has a yellowish to creamish silky, moist, slightly slimy broadly convex pileus. The pileus is radially fibrillose to smooth with a rolled margin and central to lateral stipe. The pileus is 6-10cm in diameter. The stipe is smooth, slightly fibrillose, hollow, equal in shape, 3-6cm in length. The gills are free, even and the lamellae are regular with 2-4mm apart. The entire mushroom is concolourous.The base appears to be inserted to strigose. It was found in a cluster under a red oak with some fruiting bodies attached to the oak. The gills are compact and extremely close together. Additionally, it has a partial veil. SPORE PRINT: Brown ochre.

results.notes:
Laccaria cf tortilis:
Fruiting on soil beneath a Douglas fir root edge.
Very tiny in overall stature.
Cap: pale pinkish orange, , rubbery, depressed disc, incurved striate margins with paler banded/irregular margin profile.
Gills: very widely spaced, few in total.
Stem: cylindrical, scurfy/scaled back(like most Laccaria).
Odor: non-distinct.
Harvested 3 specimens.
Spore printed a single cap directly on a glass slide.
Spore print: White.
Mounted spore printed slide in KOH.
Spores: subglobose to broadly ellipsoid. Very faintly spiny(leaving outline/halo around spores). Medium-large in size. Small apiculus on one side of many spores analyzed.
Spores with this collection are far less uniformly globose/ornamented than L. tortilis sensu stricto examples I reviewed. Perhaps a variety/subspecies.
Dehydrated all specimens and bagged for herbarium collection/genetic record.

results.notes:
Fruiting near a drainage beneath Western red cedar and red Alder.
Completely viscid/glutinous from top to bottom.
